  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized frameworks for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute money laundering cases\n- Share financial intelligence and evidence across borders\n- Enable extradition and asset recovery\n\n3. Compliance Standards\n- Establish minimum requirements for financial institutions\n- Create uniform Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Mandate suspicious transaction reporting\n- Define international best practices\n\n4. Regulatory Coordination\n- Global financial institutions develop consistent compliance strategies\n- Harmonize legal definitions of money laundering\n- Create cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Information Sharing Platforms\n- Interpol financial crime databases\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Enable rapid communication between national law enforcement agencies\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International economic sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Pressure countries to strengthen AML legal frameworks\n- Potential financial and diplomatic consequences\n\nThese intersections create increasingly sophisticated approaches to combating transnational financial crimes.",
